Text: I get it. When I was 18, I was going to write for the NYTimes. No question. When I was 20, I was going to work in telecom. 100% sure. But now I'm an English professor. That zig-zagged line through careers happens a lot.
Name: James Brown

Text: Students come to @Rutgers_Camden recruitment days convinced that they know what they want to do for the rest of their lives. And instead of asking them to question that idea, we feed it.
Name: James Brown

Text: One way to avoid this is to begin the relationship between student and university a different way, by pitching an undergraduate degree as an opportunity to find an interest or set of interests rather than a place to learn one specific profession.
Name: James Brown

Text: And when that happens, they'll have spent a long stretch of time treating the university as a place to do one specific thing rather than a place to figure out what they might like to do or what kinds of things they're interested in.
Name: James Brown

Text: A student is very likely going to change majors while on campus. And if they don't change majors, they're going to change careers after they've left the university.

Text:
"The man who built the retweet" actually just took the innovation of users and made it a button. So, what did he really build?

https://t.co/1mufbysZKh
Name: James Brown

Text: This has been a common refrain, one that ignores how the quote tweet is often used by targets of abuse to lay bare the extraordinary amount of harassment they endure on this platform.
Name: James Brown

Text: But on top of this problem, there is the issue of demonizing the quote tweet, which is called "the biggest problem" by former Twitter product head Jason Goldman. He says it's nothing more than a tool for "dunking."
Name: James Brown

Text: He automated a process without thinking through the ramifications of that automation. Once again, no one in the room asked: "What's the worst that could happen?" And that's literally the very first question people should be asking.
Name: James Brown

Text: The quote tweet is not "the biggest problem." The biggest problem is that this platform and others ask users (most often, black and brown women) to manage abuse and harassment rather than actually doing something about it.
Name: James Brown

Text: Those experiencing this not only quote that abuse but often comment on it. They are essentially teaching the rest of us how this platform actually works.
Name: James Brown

Text: These folks use the quote tweet to show us what they experience on a regular basis. Abusive tweets are aimed at a single target in an attempt to silence that target. The quote tweet bounces that abuse back out to the network.
Name: James Brown

Text: The quote tweet is more than a "dunk mechanism." It is used by many (@rgay, @tressiemcphd, @jemelehill, @EmilyGorcenski just to name a few) to bring harassment out into the open and show everyone who is managing toxicity for the rest of us.
Name: James Brown

Text: @_sarah_fischer_ For me, templates and formats are productive constraints. They offer students a maze to escape from, a game to play. Samples can be great too, as long as students are instructed in the art of imitation. So I don’t think you have to choose!
Name: James Brown

Text: @_sarah_fischer_ That said: Samples can be stifling if students treat them as madlibs. The key is to reinvent through imitation, and that’s hard to learn and hard to teach.
Name: James Brown
